<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Highlights of our 2012 financial and business performance. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Once again, we&#146;re mailing to our shareholders a Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials with instructions on how to access these materials and vote online. We believe electronic delivery expedites
the receipt of materials, lowers costs and reduces the environmental impact of our Annual Meeting. If you receive a Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials by mail, you won&#146;t receive paper copies of these materials unless you
specifically request them by following the instructions on the Notice. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Your vote is important, so we encourage you to vote promptly. The Notice
contains instructions on how to vote via the Internet or by calling a toll-free number. If you receive paper copies of the proxy materials, you may also vote by signing, dating and mailing your proxy card or voting instruction form. You may also
vote in person at the Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Highlights of Our 2012 Financial and Business Performance </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">2012 was a transformational year for our company. During the first nine months, we intensely prepared for the spin-off of our North American grocery business. The
separation of Kraft Foods Inc. into two world-class companies was a massive undertaking, culminating in a significant increase in shareholder value and the successful launch of both Mondel&#275;z International and Kraft Foods Group on
October&nbsp;1. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">What&#146;s more, we executed all of this while delivering solid business results. The quality of our revenue and earnings growth in
2012 provides strong momentum as we enter 2013. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">1 </FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Multiple Competitive Advantages </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">I&#146;m truly excited about our future as we continue our journey as a more focused company. We now have <U>all</U> the ingredients in place for sustainable, profitable growth: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="36%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="35%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="27%"></TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" COLSPAN="3"> <P STYLE="margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-2.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We have an <B>advantaged geographic footprint</B> with a significant presence in
developing markets. With more than 40 percent of our sales from Latin America, Asia Pacific, Eastern Europe, the Middle East and Africa, we&#146;re well-positioned to take advantage of GDP growth per capita in these markets. In developed markets, we
also hold advantaged positions, with nearly 40 percent of revenue coming from Europe and about 20 percent from North America.</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="right">


<IMG SRC="g468257g78y74.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:36px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We&#146;re focused on large, <B>fast-growing snacks categories. </B> </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" ROWSPAN="2"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Nearly three-quarters of our $35 billion in net revenue comes from snacks, and we&#146;re a leader in each of our core categories.
We&#146;re No.&nbsp;1 in Biscuits, Chocolate, Candy and Powdered Beverages, and a strong No. 2 in Gum and Coffee</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex"></SUP></FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">.</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">2</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In addition, growth in these categories remains robust. Globally, the Biscuits and Chocolate
categories have each grown 6 percent annually since 2009. Gum and Candy grew 5 percent, while Coffee and Powdered Beverages were up 10 percent and 7 percent, respectively</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex"></SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">.</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">2</SUP></FONT>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex"></SUP>In December 2012, we announced a reorganization of our management and reporting
structure following the spin-off of Kraft Foods Group. Beginning in 2013, our operations, management and operating segments will reflect: Asia Pacific; Eastern Europe, Middle East&nbsp;&amp; Africa (&#147;EEMEA&#148;); Europe; Latin America and
North America. Accordingly, we will begin reporting on our new segment structure during the first quarter of 2013, including all historical periods we present. For purposes of this presentation the above pie chart reflects this structure based on
our 2012 Net Revenues. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We have an <B>unrivaled portfolio of beloved Power Brands </B>and<B> proven global innovation platforms</B>. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">

<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Our portfolio features nine billion-dollar brands, including icons such as <I>Cadbury</I>, <I>Cadbury Dairy Milk</I> and
<I>Milka</I> chocolate, <I>Jacobs</I> coffee, <I>LU</I>, <I>Nabisco</I> and <I>Oreo</I> biscuits, <I>Tang</I> powdered beverages and <I>Trident</I> gum. Our pantry includes another 52 brands that each generate annual revenues of more than $100
million.</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px; margin-left:2.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We&#146;re also building a robust pipeline of
innovation platforms &#150; including <I>belVita</I> and <I>Barni </I>biscuits, <I>Bubbly</I> and bite-sized chocolate as well as <I>Tassimo</I> and <I>Millicano </I>on-demand coffee &#150; that can be expanded quickly across multiple markets to
drive growth.</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="right">


<IMG SRC="g468257g60c36.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We&#146;re building a sales execution powerhouse, leveraging strategic customer partnerships, <B>advantaged routes to market</B> and superior execution at the
point of sale, to deliver snacking solutions anywhere, at any time. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We&#146;re expanding distribution in traditional
trade channels, particularly in markets like Brazil, India and China. And in modern grocery stores, we&#146;re increasing penetration in immediate consumption channels and in the Hot Zone at the front of the stores. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In many places around the globe, we have tremendous opportunities to enter &#147;white space&#148; markets by leveraging our strong presence in one
category to enter another. For example, in 2011, we introduced <I>Oreo</I> into India building on our strong chocolate infrastructure. Just last August, we introduced <I>Stride</I> gum in China, building on our substantial infrastructure in
biscuits. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Bringing it all together, we have <B>world-class leadership, talent and capabilities </B>to execute our strategies. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Fueling the Virtuous Cycle to Drive Top-Tier Growth </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Our
strong track record of delivering results over the past few years has been driven by a virtuous growth cycle. This cycle is the framework we use to manage our company to ensure sustainable growth on both the top and bottom lines. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:18px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="42%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="57%"></TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The virtuous cycle begins with a sharp focus on our Power Brands and the core categories that will drive top-tier growth in each region. In 2012, our Power Brands, which represent almost 60
percent of total revenue, continued to drive our top line. These brands were up 8 percent last year. That&#146;s nearly <U>twice</U> the growth rate of the total company.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">


<IMG SRC="g468257g41t40.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">3 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">At the same time, we expand gross margin through a combination of pricing to recover input costs, strong productivity
and improving product mix. Last year, we increased our gross margin by 70 basis points and our adjusted gross margin</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">3</SUP></FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"> by 50 basis points. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We&#146;re also successfully leveraging overhead costs. Overheads as a percent of revenue
declined 60 basis points in 2012, despite significant investments in sales. As a result, operating margins are also expanding. Our Adjusted Operating Income Margin</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">4</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"> was up 70 basis points last year and 110 basis points since 2010. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">By keeping a firm grasp on overheads, together with higher gross margins, we generate the fuel needed to sustain our growth. We increased our spending on advertising and consumer support by 9 percent last year to
9.4 percent of revenue. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In addition, we delivered these strong results while successfully integrating Cadbury. We generated about $800 million of cost
synergies through the end of 2012. This is above our original target of $750 million. The Cadbury acquisition is also delivering on its growth promise. To date, we&#146;ve generated about $700 million in incremental revenue. All in all, we remain on
track to reach our target of $1 billion in revenue synergies by the end of 2013, with roughly two-thirds coming from developing markets. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Generating
Strong Cash Flow, Returning Cash to Shareholders, Improving ROIC </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We expect to generate about $4 billion of free cash flow</FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">5</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"> over the next two years. This will fund the cash impact of our 2012-2014 Restructuring
Program as well as provide cash to pay dividends; leaving approximately $1 billion available for deployment over the next two years. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">This is how we
plan to use this cash: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Our first priority will be to reinvest in the business to drive top-tier growth. To support this growth, we plan to increase capital investments to approximately
5 percent of net revenues in 2013 and 2014, focusing on expanding capacity in developing markets. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Second, we&#146;ll explore opportunities for tack-on acquisitions. In particular, we&#146;ll look for opportunities in developing markets where we can gain
additional scale in our categories or distribution capabilities. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Third, we&#146;ll look to return capital to shareholders in the form of dividends and/or share buybacks. The current annual dividend of $0.52 per share will
increase over time at a lower rate than EPS growth, but with a dividend payout ratio that would not fall below 30 percent. In March 2013, our board authorized a three-year share repurchase program to offset dilution from stock options.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Fourth, we&#146;ll use our cash to pay down debt to maintain financial flexibility. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Finally, we&#146;re committed to a steady improvement in return on invested capital, targeting an increase of 30 to 50 basis points per year. Double-digit earnings growth and tight management of working capital and
capital expenditures will drive the improvement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000;width:10%">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

 <P STYLE="font-size:18px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Protecting the Well-Being of Our Planet
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">From investing in sustainable agriculture to eliminating waste and promoting healthy lifestyles, we continue to evolve the way we do business to
reduce our environmental impact and enhance our contributions to society, while delivering outstanding financial performance. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:18px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="35%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="32%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="31%"></TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" COLSPAN="3"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Since October 2012, we&#146;ve committed $600 million over 10 years through our <I>Cocoa Life</I> and <I>Coffee Made Happy</I>
initiatives to build sustainable supplies and thriving communities to benefit millions of people in the developing world. </FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g468257g98l40.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD HEIGHT="16"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="16" COLSPAN="4"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px">


<IMG SRC="g468257g46k84.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" COLSPAN="3"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Coffee Made Happy</I> is designed to help the next generation of farmers &#150; inspiring, training and building capacity to improve their livelihoods and attract new
generations back to the small-scale farming sector. Through this initiative, we&#146;ll invest a minimum of $200 million to empower one million farming entrepreneurs in Vietnam, Peru and other important coffee markets by 2020.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Cocoa Life</I> is our largest, most comprehensive cocoa sustainability effort to date. As the world&#146;s largest chocolate
company, we&#146;ll invest $400 million over the next 10 years to improve the livelihoods and living conditions of more 200,000 cocoa farmers and about one million people in cocoa-farming communities. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We also remain committed to building community partnerships that empower people with the healthy habits to achieve holistic well-being. Over the last 25 years,
we&#146;ve contributed more than $1 billion in cash and food to charitable organizations around the world. And, through our Mondel&#275;z International Foundation, we&#146;re completing our $180 million pledge to ramp up physical activity for
children and their families, while securing more fresh foods through local agriculture and better nutrition education. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">To make the biggest impact
possible, we work with leading non-governmental organizations, such as INMED Partnerships for Children in Brazil, Charities Aid Federation in Russia and Klasse 2000 in Germany, as well as Helen Keller International and Save the Children in Southeast
Asia. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">5 </FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Bullish about the Future </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In sum, we&#146;re well-positioned for sustainable, profitable growth. We have an advantaged geographic footprint; an enviable portfolio of iconic brands; strong innovation platforms; a virtuous cycle in every
geography; a long runway of future growth opportunities; and strong cash flow. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">As a result, I&#146;m bullish on the future and the ability of our
110,000 employees around the world to deliver top-tier financial results. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Thank you for your continuing support. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Best regards, </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">

<IMG SRC="g468257g88l57.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:206px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Forward-Looking Statements </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">This letter to shareholders contains a number of forward-looking statements.&nbsp;Words, and variations of words, such as &#147;expect,&#148; &#147;goals,&#148; &#147;plans,&#148; &#147;continue,&#148;
&#147;may,&#148; &#147;will,&#148; and similar expressions are intended to identify our forward-looking statements, including but not limited to, sustainable and profitable growth; our ability to take advantage of growth opportunities; our
products&#146; future revenues; our pipeline of innovation platforms; our routes to market; our ability to execute our strategies; Cadbury revenue synergies; future cash flows and uses of cash; improvement in return on invested capital; plans for
protecting the well-being of our planet; and our being bullish on the future.&nbsp;These forward-looking statements involve risks and uncertainties, many of which are beyond our control, and important factors that could cause actual results to
differ materially from those in the forward-looking statements include, but are not limited to, continued volatility of commodity and other input costs, pricing actions, increased competition, our ability to differentiate our products from retailer
brands, increased costs of sales, regulatory or legal restrictions, actions or delays, a shift in our product mix to lower margin offerings, private label, risks from operating globally, continued consumer weakness, weakness in economic conditions,
our labor force and tax law changes.&nbsp;For additional information on these and other factors that could affect our forward-looking statements, see our risk factors, as they may be amended from time to time, set forth in our filings with the SEC,
including our most recently filed Annual Report on Form 10-K and subsequent reports on Forms 10-Q and 8-K.&nbsp;We disclaim and do not undertake any obligation to update or revise any forward-looking statement in this letter to shareholders, except
as required by applicable law or regulation. </FONT></P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1">*</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1">Audit &#150; Audit Committee; HRCC &#150; Human Resources and Compensation Committee; GMPAC &#150; Governance, Membership and Public Affairs Committee </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1">We believe that our executive compensation program is strongly aligned with delivering
sustainable top-tier performance and reflects competitive practices for executive compensation. The program is designed to: attract, retain and motivate talented executive officers and develop world-class business leaders; support business
strategies that promote superior long-term shareholder returns; align pay and performance by making a significant portion of our Named Executive Officers&#146; and other executive officers&#146; compensation dependent on achieving financial and
other critical strategic and individual goals; and align our executive officers&#146; and shareholders&#146; interests through stock ownership guidelines, equity-based incentive awards and other long-term incentive awards that link executive
compensation to sustained and superior Total Shareholder Return. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1">The objectives described above are encouraged by basing a significant portion of total
compensation for our Chief Executive Officer and our other Named Executive Officers on achieving and sustaining exceptional short-term and long-term performance results. Each Named Executive Officer&#146;s compensation mix reflects a significant
bias toward long-term incentives, and each long-term incentive vehicle is equity-based, and therefore directly tied to the Company&#146;s share price and shareholder returns. Further, approximately half of annual long-term incentive opportunities
granted to each Named Executive Officer is granted in the form of performance shares that can be earned, if at all, based upon the satisfaction of performance goals. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1">Our &#147;Named Executive Officers&#148; are those individuals who served as our Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer during 2012 and our three other most highly compensated officers. In addition,
two of our former executives who moved to Kraft Foods Group, Inc. after the Kraft Foods Group Spin-Off are considered our Named Executive Officers for 2012. Please read &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; beginning on page&nbsp;34 and
&#147;Executive Compensation Tables&#148; beginning on page 75 for additional details about our executive compensation programs, including information about our Named Executive Officers&#146; fiscal year 2012 compensation. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>AUDITORS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1">As a matter of good governance, we are asking our shareholders to ratify the Audit Committee&#146;s
selection of PricewaterhouseCoopers as our independent auditors for 2013. We provide information on fees billed by PwC in 2012 and 2011 on page 28 of this Proxy Statement. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>SHAREHOLDER PROPOSALS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1">In accordance with SEC rules, we include in this Proxy Statement two shareholder
proposals (Items 4 and 5). The Board recommends that you vote AGAINST each of these proposals for the reasons we set forth following each proposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="line-height:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS </B></FONT></P>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">2 </FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Significant Company Events During 2012 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">2012 was another transformational year for us. We began the year as Kraft Foods Inc., a company primarily comprised of two distinct businesses &#150; a market leading North American grocery business and a
faster-growing global snack foods business. To allow each business to focus on its specific strengths and objectives, on October&nbsp;1, 2012, we spun-off Kraft Foods Group, Inc. (&#147;Kraft Foods Group&#148;), our North American grocery business,
to our shareholders (the &#147;Spin-Off&#148;). As a result of the Spin-Off, Kraft Foods Group became an independent, publicly-traded company. In connection with the Spin-Off, we also changed our name from Kraft Foods Inc. to Mondel&#275;z
International, Inc. (&#147;Mondel&#275;z International&#148; or the &#147;Company&#148;). The Spin-Off has allowed us to focus on our significant opportunities for growth as consumer demand for snacks increases around the world. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Over the past several years, we have transformed our Company, catalyzed by our acquisitions of the LU biscuits business on November&nbsp;30, 2007 and the Cadbury
business on February&nbsp;2, 2010, and culminating with the Spin-Off, from a modestly growing grocery and snacks business into a faster-growing global snacks powerhouse. Over the last three years, we have been a top-tier performer in our industry as
evidenced by our significant returns to shareholders. Our portfolio is comprised of fast-growing categories with a footprint across most major developed and developing markets. We have leading share positions globally in the Biscuits, Chocolate,
Candy and Powdered Beverages categories, and number two share positions in the Gum and Coffee categories. With 74% of our revenue in 2012 generated in the fast-growing snacks categories, we are well positioned to deliver top-tier growth into the
future. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Further, prior to the Spin-Off, on June&nbsp;26, 2012, the Company transferred its stock exchange listing from the New York Stock Exchange to
the NASDAQ Global Select Market (&#147;NASDAQ&#148;). The Company&#146;s stock now trades on NASDAQ under the symbol &#147;MDLZ,&#148; and Kraft Foods Group trades under the symbol &#147;KRFT.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Like the Company, the Board of Directors underwent significant changes during 2012 in connection with the Spin-Off: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

effective immediately before the Spin-Off, to become directors of Kraft Foods Group; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc468257_2"></A>ITEM&nbsp;1. ELECTION OF DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_3"></A>Process for Nominating Directors </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Governance, Membership and Public Affairs Committee of our Board of Directors (the &#147;Governance Committee&#148;) is responsible for identifying, evaluating
and recommending to the Board nominees for election at the 2013 Annual Meeting of Shareholders (and any adjournments or postponements of the meeting) (the &#147;Annual Meeting&#148;). The Governance Committee relies on nominee suggestions from the
directors, shareholders, management and others. From time to time, the Governance Committee retains executive search and board advisory firms to assist in identifying and evaluating potential nominees. The Governance Committee retained
Heidrick&nbsp;&amp; Struggles to assist in the Committee&#146;s recruitment of individuals to replace two directors who did not stand for re-election at the 2012 Annual Meeting of Shareholders (Ajaypal S. Banga and Richard A. Lerner) and the five
individuals (Myra M. Hart, Peter B. Henry, Terry J. Lundgren, Mackey J. McDonald and John C. Pope) elected at the 2012 Annual Meeting of Shareholders whom the Board asked to serve on the board of Kraft Foods Group in connection with the Spin-Off.
The Committee&#146;s recruitment efforts focused on identifying individuals for the new Mondel&#275;z International Board of Directors. These recruitment efforts resulted in the Board&#146;s appointment of Stephen F. Bollenbach, Lewis W.K. Booth,
Patrick T. Siewert and Ruth J. Simmons as new directors of Mondel&#275;z International at or soon after the Spin-Off. These directors were all identified by Heidrick&nbsp;&amp; Struggles and recommended to the Board as director nominees by the
Governance Committee. Ratan N. Tata was recommended to the Board as a director nominee by the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>General
Qualifications </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board believes all directors should possess certain personal characteristics, including integrity, sound business judgment and
vision, to serve on our Board. We believe these characteristics are necessary to establish a competent, ethical and well-functioning Board that best represents the interests of our business, shareholders, employees, business partners and consumers.
Under our Corporate Governance Guidelines (the &#147;Guidelines&#148;), when evaluating the suitability of individuals for nomination, the Governance Committee takes into account many factors. These include the individual&#146;s general
understanding of the varied disciplines relevant to the success of a large, publicly traded company in a global business environment, understanding of our global businesses and markets, professional expertise and education. The Governance Committee
also considers an individual&#146;s ability to devote sufficient time and effort to fulfill his or her Mondel&#275;z International responsibilities, taking into account the individual&#146;s other commitments. In addition, the Board considers
whether an individual meets various independence requirements, including whether his or her service on boards and committees of other organizations is consistent with our conflicts of interest policy. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; "><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In addition, under the Guidelines, the Committee generally will not recommend and the Board will not nominate an individual or re-nominate for
election an independent director after he or she reaches age 75. However, from time-to-time, the Board may do so in extraordinary circumstances if the Board believes that nomination or renomination is in the shareholders&#146; best interests because
the candidate is uniquely qualified to contribute to the Board&#146;s work and Corporation&#146;s growth in the subsequent year. If the Committee determines that the individual&#146;s nomination or director&#146;s re-nomination is in the
shareholders&#146; best interests, the Committee may recommend, and the Board may approve, the nomination or re-nomination for up to three annual terms following his or her 75</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"> birthday. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In considering
whether to nominate Mr.&nbsp;Tata, age 75, for election by the Company&#146;s shareholders, both the Committee and Board reviewed Mr.&nbsp;Tata&#146;s unique experience and expertise in leading a successful global enterprise; in Indian, Asian, and
emerging markets business and cultural affairs; support for the development and promotion of innovative business practices; and insights into the continuing evolution of consumer products. They both determined that Mr.&nbsp;Tata would uniquely
contribute to the Board&#146;s work and the Corporation&#146;s growth during the coming year. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">An employee director must resign from the Board upon
ceasing to be a Company officer. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">4 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Diversity </U></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Guidelines provide that the Governance Committee will consider factors that promote diversity of views and experience when evaluating the suitability of
individuals for nomination. While the Board has no formal written policy regarding what specific factors would create a diversity of views and experience, the Governance Committee recognizes the significant benefit diversity provides to the Board
and Mondel&#275;z International, as varying viewpoints contribute to a more informed and effective decision-making process. The Governance Committee seeks broad experience in relevant industries, professions and areas of expertise important to our
operations, including global business, manufacturing, marketing, science, finance and accounting, academia, law and government. The Governance Committee also recognizes the importance of having directors with significant international experiences
and backgrounds given our global, multicultural business. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">As shown below, our director nominees have varied experiences, backgrounds and personal
characteristics, which provide the Board with a diversity of viewpoints and enable it to effectively represent our business, shareholders, employees, business partners and consumers: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Individual Skills and Experience </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Governance Committee works with the Board to determine the appropriate
mix of backgrounds and experiences that would establish and maintain a Board that is strong in its collective knowledge, allowing the Board to fulfill its responsibilities and best perpetuate our long-term success and represent our
shareholders&#146; interests. Then, when evaluating potential director nominees, the Governance Committee considers each individual&#146;s professional expertise and educational background in addition to the general qualifications. The Governance
Committee evaluates each individual in the context of the Board as a whole. To help the Governance Committee determine whether director nominees qualify to serve on our Board and would contribute to the Board&#146;s current and future needs,
director nominees complete questionnaires regarding their backgrounds, qualifications, skills and potential conflicts of interest. Additionally, the Governance Committee annually conducts evaluations of the Board and the Board&#146;s committees, and
coordinates individual directors&#146; self-assessments, that assess the experience, skills, qualifications, diversity and contributions of each individual and of the group as a whole. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Governance Committee regularly communicates with the Board to identify characteristics, professional experience and areas of expertise that are particularly desirable for our directors to possess to help meet
specific Board needs, including: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board believes that all the director nominees for election at the Annual Meeting are highly qualified. Each director nominee&#146;s specific skills, knowledge and experience that the Governance Committee relied
upon when determining whether to nominate the individual for election are described below in the nominee&#146;s biography. (A particular nominee may possess other skills, knowledge or experience even though they are not indicated.) As their
biographies indicate, the nominees have significant leadership, professional experience, knowledge and skills that qualify them for service on our Board. They represent diverse views, experiences and backgrounds. Each nominee other than the Chairman
satisfies independence requirements under the NASDAQ Stock Market Listing Standards and the Board&#146;s categorical standards of director independence. All director nominees satisfy the criteria set forth in our Guidelines and possess the personal
characteristics that are essential for the proper and effective functioning of the Board. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">All Board members are subject to annual election. Our Board
currently has ten directors, all of whom are standing for election at the 2013 Annual Meeting. Shareholders elected six of the directors to one-year terms at the 2012 Annual Meeting. The Board appointed the other four directors &#150; Messrs.
Bollenbach, Booth, and Siewert and Dr.&nbsp;Simmons &#150; in October 2012 in connection with the Spin-Off. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Governance Committee recommended, and
the Board nominated, each of the 11 director nominees listed below for election at the Annual Meeting. The terms of all directors elected at the 2013 Annual Meeting will end at the 2014 Annual Meeting or until the director&#146;s successor has been
duly elected and qualified. Each nominee has consented to his or her nomination for election to the Board. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The chart below presents information
regarding each director nominee as of April&nbsp;1, 2013, including information about each nominee&#146;s professional experience, educational background and qualifications that led the Board to nominate him or her for election. It also includes
information about all public company directorships each nominee currently holds and held during the past five years. In addition to the public company directorships listed below, the nominees also serve on the boards of various charitable,
educational and cultural institutions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The persons named as proxies on each shareholder&#146;s proxy card will vote the shares represented by the proxy
card FOR or AGAINST the director nominees or ABSTAIN from voting, as indicated in the shareholder&#146;s voting instructions. If a director nominee should become unavailable to serve as a director, the persons named as proxies intend to vote the
shares for a replacement nominee designated by the Board. In lieu of naming a substitute, the Board may reduce the number of directors on our Board. </FONT></P>

Simmons</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">President Emerita, Brown University</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Director&nbsp;since&nbsp;October 2012</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Current Committees:</FONT></P>

Compensation</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Governance, Membership and Public Affairs</FONT></P>

Africana Studies at Brown since 2001. Prior to that, Dr. Simmons served as President, Smith College from 1995 to 2001 and Vice Provost of Princeton University from 1991 to 1995. She served in various administrative positions at colleges and
universities since 1977, including the University of Southern California from 1979 to 1983, Princeton University from 1983 to 1989 (and again from 1991 to 1995) and Spelman College from 1989 to 1991.</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Education:</I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I></I>Dr. Simmons received a Bachelor of Arts in French from Dillard University and a Master of Arts and Doctor of Philosophy in Romance Languages and Literatures from Harvard University.<I></I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Public Company Boards:</I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT

<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Director Qualifications:</I></FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc468257_5"></A>CORPORATE GOVERNANCE </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We believe that a strong corporate governance framework is essential to the long-term success of our Company. This section describes our governance policies, key
governance practices, Board leadership structure and oversight functions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board reviewed our various corporate governance documents and practices
in connection with the Company&#146;s decision to delist its Class&nbsp;A Common Stock from the New York Stock Exchange and list the Class&nbsp;A Common Stock with NASDAQ beginning on June&nbsp;26, 2012 and also in preparation for the Spin-Off to
provide that they are consistent with Mondel&#275;z International&#146;s future governance needs and objectives. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_5a"></A>Corporate Governance Materials Available on Our Website </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We include the following documents in the Corporate Governance section of our website at <U><I>www.mondelezinternational.com/investor/corporate-governance/index.aspx</I></U>. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

on our website is not, and will not be deemed to be, a part of this Proxy Statement or incorporated into any of our other filings with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;). </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_6"></A>Governance Guidelines and Codes of Conduct </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Corporate Governance Guidelines </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board has adopted Corporate Governance Guidelines (the
&#147;Guidelines&#148;) that articulate our governance philosophy, practices and policies in a range of areas, including: the Board&#146;s role and responsibilities; composition and structure of the Board; establishment and responsibilities of the
committees of the Board; CEO and Board performance evaluations; and succession planning. At least annually, the Board&#146;s Governance Committee reviews the Guidelines and recommends any changes to the Board. Shareholders and others can access the
Guidelines on our website as described above. Please read &#147;Key Corporate Governance Practices&#148; beginning on page 17. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Code of Business
Conduct and Ethics for Non-Employee Directors and Code of Conduct for Employees </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We have adopted a Code of Business Conduct and Ethics for
Non-Employee Directors (the &#147;Directors Ethics Code&#148;). It fosters a culture of honesty and integrity, focuses on areas of ethical risk, guides non-employee directors in recognizing and handling ethical issues and provides mechanisms to
report unethical conduct. Annually, each non-employee director must acknowledge in writing that he or she has received, reviewed and understands the Directors Ethics Code. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We also have a Code of Conduct that applies to all of our employees. It includes a set of employee policies that cover ethical and legal practices for nearly every aspect of our business. The Code of Conduct
reflects our values, the foremost being <I>trust</I>, and contains important rules our employees must follow when conducting business to promote compliance and integrity. The Code of Conduct is part of our global compliance and integrity program
that provides support and training throughout </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">16 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">
our Company and encourages reporting of wrongdoing by offering anonymous reporting options and a non-retaliation policy. Shareholders and others can access our Code of Conduct on our website at
<U>www.mondelezinternational.com/DeliciousWorld/compliance-integrity/index.aspx</U>. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We will disclose in the Corporate Governance section of our
website any amendments to our Directors Ethics Code or Code of Conduct and any waiver granted to an executive officer or director under these codes. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_7"></A>Key Corporate Governance Practices </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We design our corporate governance practices to enhance the Board&#146;s independent leadership, accountability and oversight: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Leadership Structure. </I>As described further below under &#147;Board Leadership Structure,&#148; our Guidelines currently provide that the Chief Executive
Officer (&#147;CEO&#148;) currently serves as Chairman of the Board and an independent director serves as Lead Director. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

member of management to serve as a director. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Independent Committees</I>. The Board determined that all Board committees should consist entirely of independent directors. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Executive Sessions</I>. At each Board meeting, our independent directors meet without the Chief Executive Officer or any other members of management present
to discuss issues important to Mondel&#275;z International, including matters concerning management. These sessions are chaired by the Lead Director. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Stock Holding Requirements</I>. Our Guidelines provide that directors are expected to hold Mondel&#275;z International common stock in an amount equal to five
times the annual Board retainer within five years of joining the Board. As of March 1, 2013 all directors who have served for five years have satisfied or exceeded this holding requirement. Directors must hold equity grants awarded in May 2010 or
thereafter until six months after the director concludes service on the Board. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_8"></A>Board Leadership

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Combined Chairman and CEO </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Our By-Laws provide the Board flexibility in determining its leadership structure, permitting one person to hold the offices of chief executive officer and chairman, and providing that the Board may appoint, and
designate the duties of, a lead director. The Board periodically evaluates our leadership structure to determine whether the current structure is in our best interests based on circumstances existing at the time. When determining the leadership
structure that will allow the Board to effectively carry out its responsibilities and best represent our shareholders&#146; interests, the Board considers various factors, including our specific business needs, our operating and financial
performance, industry conditions, the economic and regulatory environment, Board and committee annual self-evaluations, advantages and disadvantages of alternative leadership structures and our corporate governance practices. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Guidelines currently provide that the Chief Executive Officer serves as Chairman of the Board and an independent director serves as Lead Director. The Board
believes that this leadership structure best meets our current and anticipated needs, as it has provided an effective balance of strong leadership and independent oversight during the last several years. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld has served as our Chief
Executive Officer and a director since June 2006. In 2007, the Board concluded that Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld should also serve as Chairman because of her extensive knowledge of the Company, the food industry and the competitive environment, her leadership
experience and her dedication to working closely with the Lead Director and our other directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Having one individual serve as both Chief Executive
Officer and Chairman benefits Mondel&#275;z International and our shareholders by contributing to the Board&#146;s efficiency and effectiveness. The Board believes that the Chief Executive Officer is generally in the best position to inform our
independent directors about our global operations and issues important to Mondel&#275;z International. Combining these roles also allows timely communication between management and the Board on critical business matters given the complexity and
geographic reach of our business and ensures alignment of our business and strategic plans. At the same time, as described below under &#147;Independent Director Leadership and Oversight,&#148; we believe that our governance practices ensure that
skilled and experienced independent directors provide independent leadership. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Independent Director Leadership and Oversight </U></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Because the Board believes that independent Board leadership is important, it established the role of Lead Director for times when one individual serves as
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer. The Lead Director is an independent director who serves as the principal liaison between the Chairman and the other independent directors and has similar responsibilities to those of the Chairman. The Board
created the Lead Director position to increase the Board&#146;s effectiveness and promote open communication among independent directors. The Lead Director works with the Chairman and other members of the Board to provide independent leadership of
the Board&#146;s affairs on behalf of our shareholders. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Under the Guidelines, the Lead Director, in consultation with the other independent directors,
is responsible for: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">advising the Chairman as to an appropriate schedule of Board meetings; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">reviewing and providing the Chairman with input regarding the agendas and materials for the Board meetings; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">presiding at all Board meetings at which the Chairman is not present, including executive sessions of the non-employee directors, and, as appropriate, apprising
the Chairman of the issues considered; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">being available for consultation and direct communication with our shareholders; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">serving as an unofficial member of all Board committees of which he or she is not a member; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">performing such other duties as the Board may from time-to-time delegate. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">18 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Our current Lead Director is Mark D. Ketchum, whom the Board appointed to that position in 2009. The Board believes
that Mr.&nbsp;Ketchum is an effective Lead Director due to his independence, leadership and operating experience from formerly serving as President and Chief Executive Officer of a global consumer products company and his corporate governance
experience acquired while serving on public company boards. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_9"></A>Director Independence </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Guidelines require that at least 75% of the directors on our Board meet the NASDAQ listing standards&#146; independence requirements and provide that the
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer generally should be the only member of management to serve as a director. For a director to be considered independent, the Board must affirmatively determine, after reviewing all relevant information, that a
director has no relationship with Mondel&#275;z International or any of its subsidiaries that would interfere with the exercise of independent judgment in carrying out the responsibilities of a director. To assist in this determination, the Board
adopted categorical standards of director independence, including whether a director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family has any current or past employment or affiliation with Mondel&#275;z International or our independent auditors.
These categorical standards are listed as Annex A to the Guidelines, which are available on our website at <U><I>www.mondelezinternational.com/investor/corporate-governance/index.aspx</I></U>. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board determined that, under our categorical standards and NASDAQ&#146;s listing standards, the following director nominees are independent: Stephen F.
Bollenbach, Lewis W.K. Booth, Lois D. Juliber, Mark D. Ketchum, Jorge S. Mesquita, Fredric G. Reynolds, Patrick T. Siewert, Ruth J. Simmons, Ratan N. Tata, and Jean-Fran&ccedil;ois M.L. van Boxmeer. In addition, the Board previously determined that
Myra M. Hart, Peter B. Henry, Terry J. Lundgren, Mackey J. McDonald and John C. Pope (who served on the Board until October&nbsp;1, 2012) and Ajaypal S. Banga and Richard A. Lerner (who served on the Board until May&nbsp;23, 2012) were independent
directors. Irene B. Rosenfeld is not independent because she is an employee of Mondel&#275;z International. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In making its determination that
Mr.&nbsp;Tata is independent, the Board considered transactions that occurred since the beginning of 2010 between Mondel&#275;z International and Tata Consultancy Services (&#147;TCS&#148;), a Tata Group company, relating to information technology
services. Mr.&nbsp;Tata formerly served as Chairman of Tata Sons Limited (the holding company of the Tata Group), TCS and several other Tata Group companies and currently serves as Chairman of the Tata Trusts. The Board considered the fact that, as
of December&nbsp;28, 2012, Mr.&nbsp;Tata ceased serving as Chairman of TCS, as well as Tata Sons Limited and other Tata Group companies, and that the transactions between Mondel&#275;z International and TCS constituted less than 0.3% of TCS&#146;s
annual revenues in each of the past three years. The Board further considered the fact that the Tata Trusts are a majority shareholder of Tata Sons Limited, but the Tata Trusts have no authority to exercise, and do not exercise, operational control
of Tata Sons Limited or the Tata Group companies. Mr.&nbsp;
Tata owns less than 1% of the outstanding shares of Tata Sons Limited. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_10"></A>Oversight of Risk Management </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Our business faces various risks, including strategic, financial, legal, regulatory, operational, accounting and reputational risks. Management is responsible for
the day-to-day assessment, management and mitigation of risk. Identifying, managing and mitigating our exposure to these risks and effectively overseeing this process are critical to our operational decision-making and annual planning processes. Our
Board has ultimate responsibility for risk oversight, but it has delegated primary responsibility for overseeing risk assessment and management to the Audit Committee. Pursuant to its charter, the Audit Committee reviews and discusses risk
assessment and risk management guidelines, policies and processes utilized in our Enterprise Risk Management (&#147;ERM&#148;) approach. Our ERM approach is an ongoing process effected at all levels of our operations and across business units to
identify, assess, monitor, manage and mitigate risk. Our ERM approach facilitates open communication between management and the Board to ensure that the Board and committees </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">19 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">
understand our risk management process, how it is functioning, the participants in the process, key risks to our business and performance and the information gathered through the approach. The
Audit Committee annually reviews our ERM process, as well as the results of our annual ERM risk assessment, to assure the process continues to function effectively. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Annually, the Audit Committee reviews and approves management&#146;s recommendation for allocating responsibility for reviewing and assessing key risk exposures and management&#146;s response to those exposures to
the full Board or retaining those responsibilities. Management provides reports to the Board and Audit Committee, in advance of meetings, regarding these key risks and the actions management has taken to monitor, control and mitigate these risks.
Management also attends Board and Audit Committee meetings to discuss these reports and provide any updates. The Audit Committee reports key risk discussions to the Board following its meetings. Board members may also further discuss the risk
management process directly with members of management. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In addition to our ERM approach, throughout the year, the Board and each committee review and
assess risks related to our business and operations as follows: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
