<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1">For a discussion about risk oversight relating to our compensation programs, see &#147;Human Resources and Compensation Committee &#150; Analysis of Risk in the Compensation
Architecture.&#148; </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board frequently discusses our strategic plans, issues and opportunities in light of circumstances in the food
and beverage industry and the economic environment. Additionally, the Board devotes several days each year to a highly focused review of our strategic plans, which includes discussion of strategic and operational risks. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board believes our current leadership structure enhances its oversight of risk management because our Chief Executive Officer, who is ultimately responsible
for our risk management process, is in the best position to discuss with the Board these key risks and management&#146;s response to them by also serving as Chairman. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_11"></A>Review of Transactions with Related Persons </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board has adopted a written policy
regarding the review, approval or ratification of &#147;related person transactions.&#148; A related person transaction is one in which Mondel&#275;z International is a participant, in which the amount involved exceeds $120,000 and in which any
&#147;related person&#148; had, has or will have a </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">20 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">
direct or indirect material interest. In general, &#147;related persons&#148; are the following persons and their immediate family members: our directors, executive officers and shareholders
beneficially owning more than 5% of our outstanding common stock. In accordance with this policy, the Governance Committee reviews transactions that might qualify as related person transactions. If the Committee determines that a transaction
qualifies as a related person transaction, then the Committee reviews, and approves, disapproves or ratifies the related person transaction. The Committee approves or ratifies only those related person transactions that are fair and reasonable to
Mondel&#275;z International and in our and our shareholders&#146; best interests. The chair of the Committee reviews and approves or ratifies potential related person transactions when it is not practicable or desirable to delay review of a
transaction until a committee meeting. The chair reports to the Committee any transaction so approved or ratified. The Committee, in the course of its review and approval or ratification of a related person transaction under this policy, considers,
among other things: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">the commercial reasonableness of the transaction; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">the materiality of the related person&#146;s direct or indirect interest in the transaction; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">whether the transaction may involve an actual, or the appearance of a, conflict of interest; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">the impact of the transaction on the related person&#146;s independence (as defined in the Guidelines and the NASDAQ listing standards); and
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">whether the transaction would violate any provision of our Directors Ethics Code or Code of Conduct or the Code of Conduct for Compliance and Integrity.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Any member of the Committee who is a related person with respect to a transaction under review may not participate in the
deliberations or decisions regarding the transaction. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">On January&nbsp;30, 2013, BlackRock, Inc. (&#147;BlackRock&#148;), an investment management
corporation, filed a Schedule 13G with the SEC notifying the Company that it became a greater than 5% shareholder as of December&nbsp;31, 2012.&nbsp;During 2012, BlackRock acted as an investment manager with respect to certain investment options
under 401(k) plans for our U.S. employees sponsored by our U.S. operating company, Mondel&#275;z International Global LLC.&nbsp;BlackRock was selected as an investment manager for the 401(k) plans by the plans&#146; named fiduciary for investment,
the Benefits Investment Committee (&#147;BIC&#148;).&nbsp;Participants in the 401(k) plans pay BlackRock&#146;s investment management fees if they invest in investment options managed by BlackRock. During 2012, BlackRock received approximately
$330,000 in connection with its investment management fees.&nbsp;The BIC&#146;s selection of BlackRock for the investment management services it provides the plans&#146; was based on its fiduciary determination that BlackRock&#146;s expertise met
applicable fiduciary standards and that its fees were reasonable and appropriate.&nbsp;The Governance Committee reviewed our relationship with BlackRock and ratified these transactions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_12"></A>Section&nbsp;16(a) Beneficial Ownership Reporting Compliance </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Section&nbsp;16(a) of
the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 (the &#147;Exchange Act&#148;) requires our executive officers, directors and persons who beneficially own more than 10% of our common stock to report to the SEC their ownership of our common stock and changes in
that ownership. As a practical matter, our Office of the Corporate Secretary assists our directors and executive officers by monitoring their transactions and completing and filing Section&nbsp;16(a) reports on their behalf. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We reviewed copies of reports filed pursuant to Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Exchange Act and written representations from reporting persons that all reportable
transactions were reported. Based solely on that review, we believe that during the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2012, all required filings were timely made in accordance with the requirements of the Exchange Act, except as follows:
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In May 2012, due to an administrative error, we filed a Form 3 on behalf of Mr.&nbsp;Mesquita underreporting his holdings of Mondel&#275;z International stock by
6,500 shares. Upon discovering the error, we filed an amended Form 3 reporting these shares. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In October 2012, due to an administrative error in connection with the Spin-Off, we filed a Form 3 on behalf of Tracey Belcourt, our Vice President, Strategy,
underreporting her shares of Mondel&#275;z International stock by 7,911 shares. Upon discovering the error, we filed an amended Form 3 reporting these shares. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_13"></A>Communications with the Board </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Information for shareholders and other parties
interested in communicating with the Lead Director, the Board or our independent directors, individually or as a group, is available on our website at <I><U>www.mondelezinternational.com/Investor/corporate-governance/contact_bod.aspx</U></I>. Our
Corporate Secretary forwards communications relating to matters within the Board&#146;s purview to the independent directors; communications relating to matters within a Board committee&#146;s area of responsibility to the chair of the appropriate
committee; and communications relating to ordinary business matters, such as suggestions, inquiries and consumer complaints, to the appropriate Mondel&#275;z International executive or employee. Our Corporate Secretary does not forward
solicitations, junk mail and obviously frivolous or inappropriate communications, but makes them available to any independent director who requests them. </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc468257_14"></A>BOARD COMMITTEES AND MEMBERSHIP </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Governance Committee considers and makes recommendations to the Board regarding the Board&#146;s committee structure and membership. Our Board then designates
the committee members and chairs based on the Governance Committee&#146;s recommendations. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board has adopted a written charter for each committee.
The charters define each committee&#146;s roles and responsibilities. All current standing committee charters are available on our website at <I><U>www.mondelezinternational.com/Investor/corporate-governance/index.aspx</U>. </I> </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">As mentioned above, the Board of Directors underwent significant changes during 2012 in connection with the Spin-Off. In the following tables, we lay out committee
structure and membership during the course of 2012 and indicate the number of times each committee met. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Through October&nbsp;1, 2012, the Board had
four standing committees: Audit, Finance, Human Resources and Compensation, and Governance. From January&nbsp;1 through the 2012 Annual Meeting, the committee structure and membership was: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_15"></A>Committee Membership </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>January&nbsp;1 through May&nbsp;23, 2012 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex"></SUP>The Human Resources and Compensation Committee acted twice by written consent during
2012. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_18"></A>Meeting Attendance </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We expect directors to attend all Board meetings, the Annual Meeting and all meetings of the committees on which they serve. We understand, however, that occasionally a director may be unable to attend a meeting.
The Board held 11 meetings in 2012. All directors who served for some or all of 2012 attended at least 75% of the aggregate number of meetings of the Board and all committees on which they served (held during the period that they served). All nine
then-incumbent directors attended the 2012 Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_19"></A>Audit Committee </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board established the Audit Committee in accordance with Section&nbsp;3(a)(58)(A) of the Exchange Act. The Board determined that all members of the Audit
Committee are independent within the meaning of the NASDAQ listing standards and Rule 10A-3 of the Exchange Act. The Board also determined that all Audit Committee members are able to read and understand financial statements in accordance with
NASDAQ listing standards and that Lewis W.K. Booth and Fredric G. Reynolds are <I>&#147;</I>audit committee financial experts&#148; within the meaning of SEC regulations and have financial sophistication in accordance with NASDAQ listing standards.
No Audit Committee member received any payments in 2012 from us other than compensation for service as a director. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Under its charter, the Audit
Committee is responsible for overseeing our accounting and financial reporting processes and audits of our financial statements. The Audit Committee is directly responsible for the appointment and oversight of our independent auditors, including
review of their qualifications, independence and performance. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Among other duties, the Audit Committee also oversees: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">the integrity of our financial statements, our accounting and financial reporting processes, our systems of internal control over financial reporting and
safeguarding our assets; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">our compliance with legal and regulatory requirements; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">the performance of our internal auditors and internal audit functions; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">our guidelines and policies with respect to risk assessment and risk management. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Audit Committee has established procedures for the receipt, retention and treatment, on a confidential basis, of any complaints we receive. We encourage employees and third-party individuals and organizations
to report concerns about our accounting controls, auditing matters or anything else that appears to involve financial or other wrongdoing. To report such matters, please e-mail us at: <I>mdlz-financialintegrity@mdlz.com</I>. </FONT></P>

<TD WIDTH="1%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Based upon the reports and discussions described in this report and without other
independent verification, and subject to the limitations of our role and responsibilities outlined in this report and in our written charter, we recommended to the Board, and the Board approved, that the audited consolidated financial statements be
included in Mondel&#275;z International&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2012, which was filed with the SEC on February&nbsp;25, 2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:6%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Audit Committee: </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:6%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Fredric G. Reynolds, Chair </FONT></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>The information contained in the above report will not be deemed to be &#147;soliciting material&#148; or &#147;filed&#148;
with the SEC, nor will this information be incorporated by reference into any future filing under the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, or the Exchange Act, except to the extent that Mondel&#275;z International specifically incorporates it by
reference in such filing. </I></FONT></P></div> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U><A NAME="toc468257_21"></A>Pre-Approval Policies </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Our Audit Committee&#146;s policy, which it reviews annually, is to pre-approve all audit and non-audit services provided by the independent auditors. These services may include audit services, audit-related
services, tax services and other permissible non-audit services. The pre-approval authority details the particular service or category of service that the independent auditors will perform. The Audit Committe&#146;s policy also requires management
to report at committee meetings throughout the year on the actual fees charged by the independent auditors for each category of service. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">During the
year, circumstances may arise when it may become necessary to engage the independent auditors for additional services not contemplated in the original pre-approval authority. In those instances, the committee approves the services before we engage
the independent auditors. If pre-approval is needed before a scheduled committee meeting, the committee delegated pre-approval authority to its chair. The chair must report on such pre-approval decisions at the committee&#146;s next regular meeting.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">During 2012, the Audit Committee pre-approved all audit and non-audit services provided by the independent auditors. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">27 </FONT></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Aggregate fees billed for professional services rendered by our independent auditors, PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP, for 2012 and 2011 were: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">overseeing Mondel&#275;z International&#146;s policies and programs related to corporate citizenship, social responsibility, and public policy issues significant
to Mondel&#275;z International such as sustainability and environmental responsibility; food labeling, marketing and packaging; and philanthropic and political activities and contributions; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">monitoring issues, trends, internal and external factors and relationships that may affect the public image and reputation of Mondel&#275;z International and the
food and beverage industry. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Governance Committee will consider any candidate whom a shareholder properly presents for election to
the Board in accordance with the procedures set forth in the By-Laws. The Governance Committee uses the same criteria set forth in the Guidelines to evaluate a candidate suggested by a shareholder as the Governance Committee uses to evaluate a
candidate it identifies, as described above under &#147;Item 1. Election of Directors &#150; Process for Nominating Directors,&#148; and makes a recommendation to the Board regarding the candidate&#146;s appointment or nomination for election to the
Board. After the Board&#146;s consideration of the candidate suggested by a shareholder, our Corporate Secretary will notify that shareholder whether the Board decided to appoint or nominate the candidate. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">For a description of how shareholders may nominate a candidate for election to the Board at an annual meeting of shareholders and have that nomination included in
the proxy statement for that meeting, see &#147;2014 Annual Meeting of Shareholders&#148; in this Proxy Statement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">During 2011, the Governance
Committee formed a subcommittee of the Governance Committee to assist in addressing director recruitment matters related to the Spin-Off. The directors who served on this subcommittee were: Myra M. Hart, Peter B. Henry and Lois D. Juliber. This
subcommittee held one meeting in 2012. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_24"></A>Human Resources and Compensation Committee </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U><A NAME="toc468257_25"></A>Human Resources and Compensation Committee Interlocks and Insider Participation </U></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Board has determined that all of the directors who served on the Human Resources and Compensation Committee (&#147;Compensation Committee&#148;) during 2012
are independent within the meaning of the NASDAQ listing standards. None of the Compensation Committee&#146;s members: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

shareholders included in our annual Proxy Statement. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U><A NAME="toc468257_28"></A>The Compensation Committee&#146;s Use of an
Independent Compensation Consultant </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee has retained Compensation Advisory Partners, LLC ("Compensation Advisory Partners")
since September, 2009 as its independent compensation consultant to assist the Compensation Committee in evaluating executive compensation programs and to advise the Compensation Committee regarding the amount and form of executive and director
compensation. The use of a consultant provides additional assurance that our executive and director compensation programs are reasonable, competitive and consistent with our objectives. The consultant is engaged directly by the Compensation
Committee, regularly participates in Compensation Committee meetings, including executive sessions of the Compensation Committee that exclude management, and advises the Compensation Committee with respect to compensation trends and best practices,
plan design and the reasonableness of compensation grants. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">30 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">During 2012, Compensation Advisory Partners provided the Compensation Committee advice and services, including:
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">updating the Compensation Committee on executive compensation trends, issues and regulatory developments. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2012, Compensation Advisory Partners provided no services to Mondel&#275;z International other than executive and director
compensation consulting services to the Compensation Committee. The Compensation Committee determined that Compensation Advisory Partners is independent and that of Compensation Advisory Partners&#146; work did not raise any conflicts of interest.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">At least annually, the Compensation Committee reviews the types of advice and services provided by Compensation Advisory Partners and the fees charged
for those services. Compensation Advisory Partners reports directly to the Compensation Committee on all executive and director compensation matters; regularly meets separately with the Compensation Committee outside the presence of management; and
speaks separately with the Compensation Committee chair and other members between meetings as necessary or desired. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U><A NAME="toc468257_28a"></A>Limited Role of Executive Officers in the Determination of Executive Compensation </U></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Each year, the Chief Executive Officer presents her compensation recommendations for each of the other Named Executive Officers (as described under
&#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148;), her remaining direct reports and other executive officers. The Compensation Committee reviews and discusses these recommendations with the Chief Executive Officer and has full discretion over all
recommended compensation actions. The Chief Executive Officer does not make recommendations or participate in deliberations regarding her compensation. Executive officers do not play a role in determining or recommending the amount or form of
director compensation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U><A NAME="toc468257_29"></A>Analysis of Risk in the Compensation Architecture </U></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Each year, including 2012, the Compensation Committee evaluates whether our compensation designs, policies and practices operate to discourage our executive
officers and employees from taking unnecessary or excessive risks. As described below under &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis,&#148; our compensation is designed to incentivize executives and employees to achieve the Company&#146;s
financial and strategic goals as well as individual performance goals that promote long-term shareholder returns. The compensation design discourages excessive risk-taking by executives and employees to obtain short-term benefits that may be harmful
to the Company and our shareholders in the long term. The Compensation Committee uses various strategies to mitigate risk, including: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Balancing Corporate and Business Unit Performance Measure Weighting</I>. Corporate and business unit performance measures are weighted in certain incentive
plans to encourage </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">31 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">
participants to focus on overall corporate performance as well as business unit performance. This balanced approach discourages actions that may improve business unit performance but harm our
overall corporate health. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Short-Term/Long-Term Incentive Mix</I>. The balanced mix between short-term and long-term incentives discourages executives from focusing on short-term
performance to the detriment of long-term performance. Our executive compensation is heavily weighted toward long-term incentive compensation to encourage sustainable shareholder value and ensure accountability for long-term results.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Award Caps</I>. Our compensation plans provide for a limit on annual incentive awards to discourage short-term actions that may harm our long-term interests.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Multiple Performance Measures</I>. In general, our incentive plans use multiple performance measures to discourage participants from focusing on achievement
of one performance measure at the expense of another. Our incentive plans generally also include individual performance criteria to ensure that goals do not favor achievement without regard for risks taken. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Committee Discretion</I>. In general, the Compensation Committee has discretion to reduce incentive awards based on unforeseen or unintended consequences.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Long-Term Incentive Mix</I>. The Compensation Committee uses a number of long-term equity based incentives to motivate executives to achieve long-term
financial goals and top-tier performance results. Multi-year vesting features and multi-year performance cycles of long-term incentive compensation promote sustainable shareholder value creation and long-term growth as well as encourage retention.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Stock Ownership Guidelines and Holding Requirements</I>. The Compensation Committee imposes meaningful stock ownership guidelines on our top executives that
are comparable to, or more stringent than, our Compensation Survey Group&#146;s (as defined under &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; below) median and stock holding requirements to align our executives&#146; interests with our
shareholders&#146; interests and ultimately focus our executives on attaining sustainable long-term shareholder returns. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Clawback and Anti-Hedging Policies</I>. Our clawback policy allows the Company to recapture incentive compensation paid in the event of certain restatements
of our financial statements, which discourages inappropriate risk-taking behavior. Our anti-hedging policies further align our executives&#146; interests with those of our shareholders. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Ethics and Compliance Programs</I>. The Audit Committee oversees our ethics and compliance programs that educate executives and employees on appropriate
behavior and the consequences of inappropriate actions. These programs use innovative and effective approaches to promote compliance and integrity and encourage employees and others to report concerns by providing multiple reporting avenues with a
no retaliation policy. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Governance Practices</I>. We have implemented good pay and governance practices that are critical to driving sustained shareholder value, including targeting
pay at the median of our Compensation Survey Group, using quantitative results to determine incentive awards (with a qualitative overlay where appropriate), engaging an independent compensation consultant, communicating with our shareholders to
understand their views and concerns and conducting annual risk assessments. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee also analyzed our overall
enterprise risks and whether our compensation programs could impact individual behavior so as to exacerbate these enterprise risks. The Compensation Committee collaborated with the Audit Committee in this analysis. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In addition to the Compensation Committee&#146;s evaluation, Compensation Advisory Partners also reviewed our executive and broad-based incentive plans and noted
similar terms in our incentive plans that mitigate risk. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">32 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In light of these analyses, the Compensation Committee believes that our compensation programs do not create risks
that are reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on Mondel&#275;z International. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><div style="width:100%;margin-left:0%; margin-right:0%;border:solid 1pt;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:3px">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-top:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U><A NAME="toc468257_30"></A>Human Resources and Compensation Committee Report for the Year Ended
December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2012</U> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee oversees our compensation programs on behalf of the Board.
In fulfilling its oversight responsibilities, the Compensation Committee reviewed and discussed with management the Compensation Discussion and Analysis included in this Proxy Statement. In reliance on that review and discussion, the Compensation
Committee recommended to the Board that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in our Proxy Statement to be filed with the SEC in connection with our Annual Meeting and incorporated by reference in our Annual Report on Form 10-K for
the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2012, which was filed with the SEC on February&nbsp;25, 2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:8%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Human Resources and Compensation
Committee:</B> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:8%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Lois D. Juliber, Chair </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:8%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Stephen F. Bollenbach </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:8%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Mark D. Ketchum </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:8%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Ruth J. Simmons </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; margin-left:8%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Jean-Fran&ccedil;ois M.L. van Boxmeer </FONT></P></div>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">33 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc468257_31"></A>COMPENSATION OF NON-EMPLOYEE DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Any director who is a full-time employee of Mondel&#275;z International receives no compensation for service as a director. Currently, Irene B. Rosenfeld is the
only director who is an employee of the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We strive to attract and retain highly qualified non-employee directors who will best represent our
shareholders&#146; interests. In order to ensure that the compensation offered is sufficient to meet this objective, our Compensation Committee annually reviews non-employee director compensation. As in prior years, during 2012 the Compensation
Committee used data provided by its independent compensation consultant to benchmark our non-employee director compensation against our Compensation Survey Group (discussed below in the &#147;Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis&#148;) and
compensation paid to non-employee directors of Fortune 100 companies to consider the appropriateness of the form and amount of non-employee director compensation and to make recommendations to the Board concerning such compensation. Based on the
benchmarking, the Compensation Committee determined that current total compensation levels are below median. The Compensation Committee indicated that it would reconsider compensation for non-employee directors in 2013. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Summary of Compensation Elements </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The table below
summarizes the compensation elements in effect during 2012 for our non-employee directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="50" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="7%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1">In 2012, non-employee directors, with the exception of Messrs. Pope and van Boxmeer, were awarded deferred share units (&#147;DSUs&#148;). Although the DSUs vested as of the
award date, shares of Company stock are not distributed until six months following the date the non-employee director ceases to serve on our Board. When dividends are paid on our common stock, we accrue the value of the dividend paid and issue
shares equal to the accrued value six months after the director&#146;s departure. Messrs. Pope and van Boxmeer were awarded unrestricted shares; however, the shares are subject to an equity holding restriction which ends six months after they cease
serving on our Board. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Cash Compensation </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We pay our non-employee directors their cash retainers quarterly. Non-employee directors can defer 25%, 50%, 75% or 100% of their cash retainers into notional unfunded accounts that mirror the investment options
under the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Thrift 401(k) Plan pursuant to the Mondel&#275;z International, Inc. 2001 Compensation Plan for Non-Employee Directors. A non-employee director appointed by the Board during the year receives a prorated retainer
based on the number of days remaining in the calendar year following the appointment. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Equity Compensation </U></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In addition, annually at the Board meeting immediately following our annual meeting of shareholders, the Board grants our non-employee directors stock in the
Company. A non-employee director appointed by the Board during the year receives a stock grant upon joining the Board in a prorated amount based on the following ratio: the number of months until the next annual meeting of shareholders over a
denominator of twelve months. At the non-employee director&#146;s election, he or she may receive the annual stock award in the form of (i)&nbsp;unrestricted shares of our common stock, </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">34 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">
subject to a holding period ending six&nbsp;months after the director no longer serves on our Board or (ii)&nbsp;vested DSUs where distribution of shares is deferred until six&nbsp;months after
the director no longer serves on our Board. For those non-employee directors who receive DSUs, when dividends are paid, we accrue the value of the dividend paid and issue shares equal to the accrued value six months after the director&#146;s
departure. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Equity Holding Requirement </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">To align
the interests of our shareholders and our non-employee directors further, we require that they hold shares of our common stock in an amount equal to five times the annual Board retainer (equivalent to $550,000) within five years of becoming a
director. If a non-employee director does not meet the stock ownership requirement within the timeline, the Lead Director will consider the director&#146;s particular situation and may take any further action as he deems appropriate. As of
March&nbsp;1, 2013, each director who has served for at least five years has met or exceeded this requirement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Company Matching Charitable Donations
at the Direction of a Director </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Non-employee directors may also participate in the Mondel&#275;z International Foundation Matching Gift Program on
the same terms as our U.S. employees. Under the program, the Mondel&#275;z International Foundation matches up to $15,000 of donations per director, per year, of contributions to 501(c)(3) non-profit organizations. </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="4"><B><A NAME="toc468257_32"></A>COMPENSATION DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">This Compensation Discussion and Analysis (&#147;CD&amp;A&#148;): </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Highlights our 2012 performance, our overall performance during 2010-2012 and our transformation into a global snacks powerhouse; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Summarizes the executive compensation philosophy of our Human Resources and Compensation Committee (referred to in this CD&amp;A as the &#147;Compensation
Committee&#148; or &#147;Committee&#148;); </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Describes how the Committee designs our executive compensation programs; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Shows the correlation between the Committee&#146;s compensation-related decisions and how well the Company and each executive performed over the period based on
standards established by the Committee. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><div style="width:100%;margin-left:0%; margin-right:0%;border:solid 1pt;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:3px">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-top:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_33"></A>Executive Summary </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">This Executive Summary: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Highlights our 2012 performance, our overall performance during 2010-2012 and our transformation into a global snacks powerhouse; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Identifies the key actions the Compensation Committee took to align our Named Executive Officers&#146; (referred to in our CD&amp;A as our Named Executive
Officers or &#147;NEOs&#148;) and shareholders&#146; interests; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Summarizes the Committee&#146;s compensation governance practices for 2012 to demonstrate how the Committee takes shareholder interests into account in
compensating our executives. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>During 2012, We Continued to Transform the Company </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">2012 was another transformational year for us. We began the year as Kraft Foods Inc., a company primarily comprised of two distinct
businesses&#150;a market leading North American grocery business and a faster-growing global snack foods business. To allow each business to focus on its specific strengths and objectives, on October&nbsp;1, 2012, we spun-off Kraft Foods Group, our
North American grocery business, to our shareholders. As a result of the Spin-Off, Kraft Foods Group became an independent, publicly-traded company. In connection with the Spin-Off, we also changed our name from Kraft Foods Inc. to Mondel&#275;z
International, Inc. The Spin-Off has allowed us to focus on our significant opportunities for growth as consumer demand for snacks increases around the world. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Over the past several years we have transformed our Company, catalyzed by our acquisitions of the LU biscuits
business on November&nbsp;30, 2007 and the Cadbury business on February&nbsp;2, 2010, and culminating with the Spin-Off, from a modestly growing grocery and snacks business into a faster-growing global snacks powerhouse. Over the last three years,
we have been a top-tier performer in our industry as evidenced by our significant returns to shareholders. Our portfolio is comprised of fast-growing categories with a footprint across most major developed and developing markets. We have leading
share positions globally in the Biscuits, Chocolate, Candy and Powdered Beverages categories, and number two share positions in the Gum and Coffee categories. With 74% of our revenue in 2012 generated in the fast-growing snacks categories, we are
well positioned to deliver top-tier growth into the future. </FONT></P></div>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">37 </FONT></P>

STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">These charts illustrate how Snacks increased from 37% of our portfolio in 2009 to 74% of our portfolio post Spin-Off. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

<div style="width:100%;margin-left:0%; margin-right:0%;border:solid 1pt;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:3px"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-top:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>We Delivered Strong Results During the Last Three Years of our Transformation </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Our three-year performance from 2010-2012 reflected high-single digit Operating Earnings Per Share (&#147;Operating EPS&#148;)
growth and mid-single digit Organic Net Revenue growth.&nbsp;Although we anticipated better Organic Net Revenue growth in 2012, we believe that our underlying fundamental performance has us well-positioned to deliver strong growth in the
future.&nbsp;We established Kraft Foods Group as an independent public company and completed the Spin-Off, which included successfully separating our respective businesses and adequately capitalizing both companies without significant disruption to
our business. The Spin-Off will provide us with increased focus on our ongoing operations.&nbsp;While we significantly out-performed our Performance Peer Group in shareholder return for the three-year period 2010-2012, our 2012 shareholder return
was closer to the median performance of our Performance Peer Group.&nbsp;See &#147;Our Compensation Program Design &#150; Composition and Purpose of the Performance Peer Group&#148; below for additional information regarding our Performance Peer
Group. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%;"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The chart below provides a one-year and annualized three-year review of our Total Shareholder Return
(&#147;TSR&#148;)</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">(1)</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">. </FONT></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In early 2013, the Committee reviewed our performance compared to our 2012 Annual Cash Incentive Program (&#147;Program&#148;)
objectives. Overall, despite solid growth versus prior year, we were below our Organic Revenue Growth and Defined Operating Income targets. We did, however, deliver strong Defined Free Cash Flow results. The results that drove Program payouts for

below for more information about our results relative to targets. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>2010 &#150; 2012 Performance and Impact on
Long-Term Incentive Plan (&#147;LTIP&#148;) Award </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%;"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Overall, we delivered performance above target during the
2010-2012 performance cycle for the LTIP. In 2010, the Committee set the performance cycle at three years; however, at the December 2011 Committee meeting, the period was shortened to 33 months (January 1, 2010 &#150; September&nbsp;30, 2012) to
coincide with the Spin-Off. Over the performance cycle we achieved strong Operating EPS Growth, Organic Net Revenue Growth and relative TSR. During this period, our relative TSR was above the 90</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">th</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"> percentile of our Pre Spin-Off Performance Peer Group &#150; significantly surpassing the Performance Peer Group&#146;s median.

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">With the advice of its independent consultant, the Committee structured the grant (in size and terms) to ensure
that Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld continues as the Company&#146;s CEO well into the future while further incenting her to continue delivering top-tier returns in the coming years. The award reflects the Board&#146;s confidence in Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s
ability to successfully lead the Company following the Spin-Off and ensure that a long-term management development and senior leadership succession plan is in place. </FONT></P></div>
