Compensation &#150; Long-Term Incentives &#150; Special CEO Equity Grant&#148; below for more information about the provisions of this grant. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Special Equity Grants to Select Executives Recognize Successful Execution of Spin-Off </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">On November&nbsp;13, 2012, the Compensation Committee granted select senior executives, including Mr. Brearton and Ms. West, restricted stock to reward them for their significant contributions toward the successful
execution of the Spin-Off. See &#147;&#150;&nbsp;Elements of Executive Compensation &#150; Long-Term Incentives &#150; Special Equity Grant to Select Executives to Recognize Successful Execution of Spin-Off &#147; below for more information about
these grants. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Aligning Pay with Performance </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s executive compensation philosophy is designed to promote superior long-term shareholder
returns. This objective is encouraged by basing a significant portion of total compensation for our CEO and the other NEOs on achieving and sustaining exceptional short-term and long-term performance results. The Committee not only structures each
NEO&#146;s compensation mix with a significant bias toward long-term incentives, but also designs each long-term incentive vehicle to be equity-based, and therefore directly tied to the Company&#146;s share price and shareholder returns. Further,
approximately half of annual long-term incentive opportunities granted to each NEO is granted in the form of performance shares; half of the performance share grants are based on TSR in comparison to our Performance Peer Group, 25% is based on
Organic Net Revenue Growth performance and 25% is based on Operating EPS Growth. The Committee also grants non-qualified stock options, which will only result in remuneration if the Company&#146;s stock price appreciates above the grant price at a
time when the options are exercised. See &#147;&#150;&nbsp;Elements of Executive Compensation &#150; Long-Term Incentives&#148; for more information about our long-term incentive programs. </FONT></P></div>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">41 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <div style="width:100%;margin-left:0%; margin-right:0%;border:solid 1pt;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:3px"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-top:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The chart below illustrates the alignment between CEO pay and Indexed TSR over the past 5 years. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g468257g07d50.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P></div> <P STYLE="margin-top:30px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>How the Committee Considered the Shareholder Advisory Vote on our 2011 Executive Compensation Program </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">At the 2012 Annual Meeting of Shareholders, we held our second shareholder advisory vote on NEO compensation. Our shareholders expressed strong support for our
fiscal year 2011 executive compensation program &#151; with 96.3% of votes cast voting to approve the compensation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Committee considered these
voting results when designing the 2012 NEO compensation packages. The Committee concluded that the current compensation programs are effectively aligning pay and performance and are promoting long-term shareholder value and did not make any specific
program changes as a result of the voting results. Consequently, apart from issuing one time equity grants to our CEO, CFO and one other NEO in connection with their leadership in successfully transforming the company and executing the Spin-Off, the
Committee approved only modest design changes to our ongoing compensation programs during 2012. In fulfilling its role, the Committee will continue to consider the results of future shareholder advisory votes as well as shareholder views about our
core compensation principles, objectives and program design. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">42 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>We Employ Sound Compensation Design Principles and Corporate Governance Practices </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We believe that our executive compensation design principles and governance practices provide focus, a foundation for success, and clear alignment with shareholder
interests. The chart below describes key principles and practices. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><div style="width:100%;margin-left:0%; margin-right:0%;border:solid 1pt;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:3px">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;padding-top:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B>Compensation Design Principles and Governance Practices </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Committee intends its compensation design principles to protect and promote our shareholders&#146; interests. In general, our
compensation-related governance practices are comparable to, or are more stringent than, our peers&#146; practices. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%;margin-right:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Design Principles </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Link pay to performance.</U> We reward our NEOs based upon the value of their contributions. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Put pay-at-risk based on performance.</U> Over 85% of our CEO&#146;s pay is at-risk consistent with peer companies in our Compensation Survey Group. Over 70% of our other
NEOs&#146; pay is at-risk. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Target pay at the median of our peer group.</U> We compensate fairly and competitively, but not excessively. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Do not incent short term results to the detriment of long term goals.</U> </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Do not incent excessively risky business strategies.</U> </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Governance</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Practices </I></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Require significant equity ownership.</U> Our stock ownership guidelines are comparable to, or more stringent than, our Compensation Survey Group&#146;s median. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Require executives to retain equity compensation.</U> To buttress our stock ownership guidelines, we require our NEOs to hold for one year all net shares awarded and all net
shares acquired upon the exercise of stock options. (Net shares are the number of shares delivered after applicable costs, employment and income taxes have been withheld based on the value of the gross shares awarded or stock options exercised.)
</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Provide for &#147;clawbacks&#148;.</U> Our clawback policy allows us to recoup incentive compensation in the event of certain financial restatements. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Prohibit hedging or short sales.</U> We prohibit our NEOs from hedging or entering into short sales of any equity interests in the Company. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Prohibit pledging of Company shares.</U> We prohibit NEOs and other senior level executives from pledging shares as collateral for a loan. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Limit perquisites/tax gross-ups.</U> We provide the types and amounts of perquisites at or below the median levels of peer companies in our Compensation Survey Group. We do
not gross up income to mitigate the tax impact of the perquisites provided. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>In the event of a change in control:</U> </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#216;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Pay severance and vest equity only upon a &#147;double trigger.&#148;</U> With &#147;double trigger&#148; vesting, we retain the power to make personnel decisions during a
change in control. (&#147;Double trigger&#148; requires a change in control and termination of employment without cause.) </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></div>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">43 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <div style="width:100%;margin-left:0%; margin-right:0%;border:solid 1pt;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:3px">
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#216;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Do not provide NEOs tax gross ups.</U> We do not provide NEOs or other executives tax gross-ups upon a change in control. Taxes are our NEOs&#146; responsibility. Prior to
2013, certain executives&#146; rights to tax gross ups on a change in control were &#147;grandfathered&#148;. However, effective January&nbsp;1, 2013, we eliminated this right for all executives, including &#147;grandfathered&#148; executives.
</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Do not re-price underwater stock options.</U> We do not re-price outstanding stock options &#150; vested or unvested. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Do not pay dividends on unvested or unearned performance shares.</U> Because performance shares do not vest unless the applicable performance conditions are satisfied, we do
not pay dividend equivalents for the unvested period unless and until the performance conditions are satisfied and we deliver the shares awarded. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Do not enter into employment agreements with our NEOs.</U> Executive officers do not have employment contracts and are not guaranteed salary increases or bonus amounts.
However, we agreed to provide Mr. Kholsa benefits greater than those generally provided to other employees when he retired from Mondel&#275;z International. We did so as consideration for Mr. Khosla&#146; s agreement to restrictive covenants. For
further information, see the discussion of Mr. Khosla&#146;s compensation under Compensation Paid to Named Executive Officers in 2012. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>The Compensation Committee retains an independent compensation consultant.</U> The compensation consultant does no work for the Company other than advising the Compensation
Committee. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Perform an annual compensation risk assessment.</U> Management presents the results of the assessment to the Compensation Committee and independent compensation consultant for
review. </FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#254;</FONT></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"></FONT></FONT></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Engage shareholders.</U> We strive to communicate in plain English, and we take into account shareholder concerns and input when reviewing our executive compensation program
and practices. Over the last year, Irene Rosenfeld, our Chairman and CEO, David Brearton, our Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer, and members of our Investor Relations group met with nearly 500 current or prospective institutional
shareholders to discuss the Company&#146;s strategy, financial results and outlook. During these discussions, we also addressed any questions or concerns regarding annual and long-term executive compensation structures, both current and future. We
also provided feedback from these discussions to the Compensation Committee. These discussions are part of the dialogue we have with the institutional investor community both within and outside the U.S. </FONT></TD>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_35"></A>Our Compensation Program Design </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Compensation Philosophy </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Committee regularly evaluates its compensation philosophy and makes changes it
believes are appropriate. As part of the 2012 review, the Committee considered whether changes would be desirable following the Spin-Off and concluded that no changes were necessary. The Committee also determined that the strategies designed to
achieve its compensation objectives continue to be appropriate for the Company after the Spin-Off. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Our executive compensation program has four primary
objectives: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">1.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">attract, retain and motivate talented executive officers and develop world-class business leaders; </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">2.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">support business strategies that promote superior long-term shareholder returns; </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">3.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">align pay and performance by making a significant portion of our NEOs&#146; and other executive officers&#146; compensation dependent on achieving financial and other critical
strategic and individual goals; and </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">4.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">align our executive officers&#146; and shareholders&#146; interests through stock ownership guidelines, equity-based incentive awards and other long-term incentive awards that
link executive compensation to sustained and superior TSR. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We design our executive compensation program to achieve these objectives by
following these principles and practices: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Pay competitively but not excessively.</I> Each year, the Committee compares our target and actual compensation levels and pay-mix with our Compensation
Survey Group (see &#147;Composition and Purpose of Compensation Survey Group&#148; below for definition of the Compensation Survey Group). The Committee uses this comparison to ensure that our executive compensation and benefits package is
competitive with the Compensation Survey Group but not excessive. In addition, the Committee compares our financial and TSR performance against our Performance Peer Group. The Performance Peer Group comparison
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">45 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">
allows us to link long-term incentive compensation to the delivery of superior financial results relative to industry peers. In anticipation of the Spin-Off, the Committee made changes to the
Compensation Survey Group, the Performance Peer Group and comparison methodology. See &#147;Pay Competitively, But Not Excessively&#148; below for additional details. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Use Fixed and Variable Compensation.</I> The Committee uses a mix of fixed and variable compensation (heavily weighted to variable compensation for our NEOs)
designed to attract, retain and motivate top-performing executives, as well as appropriately align compensation levels with achieving relevant financial and strategic goals; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Use Equity and Cash Incentives.</I> The Committee uses a mix of equity and cash incentives heavily weighted toward equity to focus executive officers on
achieving long-term TSR performance that is superior to our peers; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Compensate based on Individual Performance and Potential.</I> The Committee makes incentive awards based in part on the individual&#146;s performance and
potential for advancement within the organization; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Require executive officers to be significant shareholders.</I> The Committee requires our executive officers, including our NEOs, to maintain specific levels
of Company stock ownership in order to align their interests with those of our shareholders. Our compensation programs facilitate high levels of stock ownership. The Committee also requires our executive officers to hold for one year net shares
received through the exercise of stock options, the vesting of restricted stock and the award of Company stock upon satisfaction of performance conditions. More information about stock ownership guidelines for executive officers can be found below
under &#147;Requiring Stock Ownership.&#148; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Pay Competitively, But Not Excessively </U></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Peer Group Approach </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Each year, the Committee compares our
compensation program with those companies in our Compensation Survey Group. The Committee also uses a Performance Peer Group to analyze the linkage between pay and performance and to determine the Company&#146;s relative TSR ranking for the LTIP. As
a result of the Spin-Off, the Committee reviewed our Compensation Survey Group and our Performance Peer Group and adjusted both based on the Company&#146;s Post Spin-Off characteristics. For 2012, the Committee used the Post Spin-Off Compensation
Survey Group to evaluate our pay practices including stock ownership guidelines and perquisites. Pay levels reflected in 2012 (as reported in the tables below) are based on the Pre Spin-Off and Post Spin-Off Compensation Survey Groups depending on
timing of pay level decisions. For 2013, the Committee will use the Post Spin-Off Compensation Survey and Performance Peer Groups to evaluate all elements. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Composition and Purpose of the Compensation Survey Group </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Committee annually compares our compensation
program with those companies in our Compensation Survey Group to&nbsp;ensure that our compensation program and our target compensation levels are consistent with market practice. This allows us to attract and retain the talent we need to drive
superior long-term TSR performance. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">46 </FONT></P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Walt Disney Company</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Kellogg Company</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Committee used this peer group to analyze compensation levels for our named executive officers in 2012. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In anticipation of the Spin-Off, the Committee reviewed our Compensation Survey Group and determined it needed adjustment. In making the adjustments, the Committee
sought to have the Compensation Survey Group represent our market competitors, based on the Company&#146;s post Spin-Off characteristics. The Committee removed those companies with a primary focus similar to our North America grocery business,
companies whose revenue significantly decreased following divestitures such that they were no longer good points of comparison, and pharmaceutical companies with significantly lower revenue than ours. The Committee added global, top-tier, high
growth consumer products companies, global companies with manufacturing, and global consumer-facing companies. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Through this review process, the
Committee developed a Post Spin-Off Compensation Survey Group. It consists of companies within the Consumer Products industry, selected based on the following attributes: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

median revenues of $31.1 billion. Our revenue size places us above the median of the peer companies. The approved Post Spin-Off Compensation Survey Group is: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Competitive Positioning </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Generally, in determining appropriate compensation levels for our NEOs, the Committee reviews compensation levels for similarly situated executives at companies in
the Compensation Survey Group. Aon Hewitt provides that compensation data. At the request of the Committee, CAP reviews and evaluates the data that Aon Hewitt provides. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Committee&#146;s compensation philosophy is to target total direct compensation, including base salary and annual and long-term incentives, at or near the median of the Compensation Survey Group. Company
performance and individual performance will determine whether actual pay received is above or below the Compensation Survey Group median. For 2012, the Committee, using the Pre Spin-Off Compensation Survey Group, targeted a size-adjusted median
since the Company&#146;s revenues were significantly greater than the median of our peer group. Following the Spin-Off, however, our revenues now approximate the median of the Post Spin-Off Compensation Survey Group and the Committee can therefore
use the nominal median to position named executive officer compensation without size-adjusting the data. In general, the target total compensation for the Pre Spin-Off Compensation Survey Group does not differ significantly from the target total
compensation for the Post Spin-Off Compensation Survey Group. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">48 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Composition and Purpose of the Performance Peer Group </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Committee uses a performance peer group to analyze the linkage between pay and performance and to determine the Company&#146;s relative TSR ranking for the
LTIP (see discussion below under &#147;Long-Term Incentives&#148; for a description of how each outstanding performance cycle was treated upon the Spin-Off). Prior to the Spin-Off, the companies in our Performance Peer Group (the &#147;Pre Spin-Off
Performance Peer Group&#148;) were considered to be our market competitors or had been selected primarily on the basis of industry. The Pre Spin-Off Performance Peer Group included the following companies: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="47%"></TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">General Mills, Inc.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">PepsiCo, Inc.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Groupe Danone</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Sara Lee Corp.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">H.J. Heinz Company</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Unilever N.V.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In anticipation of the Spin-Off, the Committee reviewed our Pre Spin-Off Performance Peer Group and determined that adjustments
were appropriate following the Spin-Off. The Committee removed those companies with a primary focus similar to our North America grocery business and companies whose revenue significantly decreased following divestitures such that they were no
longer good points of comparison. The Committee added global, top-tier, high growth consumer products companies. The Committee then approved a new 12-company Performance Peer Group (the &#147;Post Spin-Off Performance Peer Group&#148;). The
Committee&#146;s independent compensation consultant, Compensation Advisory Partners, also provided independent analysis and advice regarding the Post Spin-Off Performance Peer Group. The historical P/E multiples and growth rates, on average, for
the companies in the revised peer group are higher than the companies in the Pre Spin-Off Performance Peer Group and better reflecting our focus on high growth markets and categories. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">There is substantial overlap (10 of the 12 companies) between the Post Spin-Off Performance Peer Group and the Post Spin-Off Compensation Survey Group. The main difference between them is that the Post Spin-Off
Performance Peer Group companies are primarily food and non-alcoholic beverage companies (9 of the 12 companies in the Performance Peer Group versus 8 of the 21 companies in the Compensation Survey Group) and are included regardless of revenue size
or market capitalization. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In considering performance measures for the LTIP, the Committee believes that our financial performance should be compared to
a group of primarily food and non-alcoholic beverage companies as our shareholders are likely comparing our financial performance to a similar group of companies when making investment decisions. The Committee believes that this group is less
relevant when comparing compensation levels for certain executive positions due to our larger size and complexity relative to several companies included in this group. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Overall Pay Mix </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The chart below shows the total compensation mix, on average, for our CEO and other NEOs, based on target awards in 2012, compared with the average of the
Compensation Survey Group. Our mix is well&#150;aligned to the mix paid by companies in the Compensation Survey Group. In the case of our CEO, the incentive mix is slightly more weighted towards long-term incentives and less weighted in annual
incentives compared to the Compensation Survey Group, consistent with our focus on delivering top-tier sustainable performance over the long-term. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Overview of 2012 Compensation Program </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The following table summarizes the elements and program objectives of our 2012 compensation program for executive officers, including NEOs. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="18%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="40%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="38%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" NOWRAP> <P STYLE="border-bottom:1px solid #000000;width:38pt"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><B>Program</B></FONT></P></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Ongoing cash compensation based on the executive officer&#146;s role and responsibilities.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Retention and attraction</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Drive top-tier performance</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px; margin-left:3.50em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#150;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Individual contribution</FONT></P></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Annual incentive with target award amounts for each executive officer. Actual cash awards may be higher or lower than target, based on business and individual performance.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Drive top-tier performance</FONT></P>

<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Performance Shares or LTIP</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Long-term incentive with target award amounts are established for each executive
officer. Actual awards are linked to achievement of three-year Mondel&#275;z International goals and can be 0% &#150; 200% of target, based on our performance. Payout will be in Mondel&#275;z International common stock following the end of the
three-year program.</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:1px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No dividends or dividend equivalents are paid or earned on unvested performance shares granted
prior to 2013. For performance shares granted beginning with the 2013-2015 performance cycle, dividend equivalents will accrue during the performance period and be paid in cash only if and when shares are delivered (i.e., after performance criteria
have been satisfied).</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Drive top-tier performance</FONT></P>

officer&#146;s career. This program is not offered to any U.S. employees hired on or after January 1, 2009 and for employees who are participating, no additional accruals will be made after 2019.</FONT></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Retention</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Attraction</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Promote executive health</FONT></P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc468257_36"></A>Elements of Executive Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Each element of the compensation program is described below and individual compensation decisions are discussed under &#147;Compensation Paid to Named Executive Officers in 2012.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Base Salary </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Base salary is the principal &#147;fixed&#148;
element of executive compensation. In setting base salary levels for NEOs, the Committee generally targets base salary to be at or near the median of the Compensation Survey Group based on the corresponding executive role. The Committee does also
consider a number of other factors when reviewing and setting base salaries for NEOs including: Company performance and the NEO&#146;s individual performance, level of responsibility, potential to assume roles with greater responsibility, and
experience. The Committee reviews salaries on an annual basis and considers merit increases, which are generally effective April&nbsp;1, for all executive officers. Base salaries for NEOs for 2012 were generally at or below the median of comparable
roles at companies comprising the Compensation Survey Group. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Annual Cash Incentive Program </U></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Overview </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Annual Cash Incentive Program
(&#147;Program&#148;) is designed to motivate our employees, including our NEOs, to help us reach our annual financial and strategy goals and to reward them for their contributions toward achieving those goals. The Committee determines each
NEO&#146;s target and maximum annual incentive opportunity at the beginning of the performance year, and the amount actually awarded under the Program is based on the financial results achieved during the year and the NEO&#146;s contribution towards
achieving those results. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">53 </FONT></P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" COLSPAN="7"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.60em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Committee chose these measures because of their high
correlation to TSR. These measures reinforce the importance of driving both top-line and bottom-line performance while generating positive cash flow.</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px; margin-left:2.60em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In establishing the performance standards under the Program for 2012, the Committee
determined that a business unit rating of 100% would result in target performance having been achieved. Where actual performance exceeds target performance, the actual business unit rating would exceed 100%, and where actual performance does not
achieve target performance, the actual business unit rating would be less than 100%.</FONT></P></TD></TR>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">54 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="18%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="3%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="79%"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" NOWRAP> <P STYLE="border-bottom:1px solid #000000;width:68pt"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><B>Award Formula<BR>Element</B></FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="border-bottom:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><B>Explanation of Key Provisions</B></FONT></P></TD></TR>


<TR BGCOLOR="#d8d8d8">
<TD VALIGN="top"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:1px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Committee weighted the business unit ratings under the Program for Messrs. Khosla and Cofer for 2012 as follows: 30% of the business unit rating would be based on their respective business unit&#146;s rating and 70% would be based on the weighted
average Company&#146;s Pre-Spin-Off/Post-Spin-Off rating. The Committee structured their performance standards in this manner to promote both &#147;line-of-sight&#148; accountability, as well as to reinforce the importance of collaboration across
the enterprise. Business unit ratings for our other NEOs were aligned 100% to the weighted average the Company&#146;s Pre-Spin-Off period and Post-Spin-Off period rating.</FONT></P></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD HEIGHT="8"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Individual Performance Ratings</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ratings range from 0% to 180%.</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ms. Rosenfeld provided the
Committee with an individual performance assessment for each of her direct reports, including our other NEOs. The Committee reviewed and discussed her recommendations, taking into account the various factors within the criteria, to determine each
direct report&#146;s individual performance rating.</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Specifically, in assessing individual performance in the context of making executive compensation decisions, Ms. Rosenfeld and the Committee considered the executive officer&#146;s
contributions to our overall performance and individual performance relative to individual objectives established at the beginning of the performance cycle.</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:1px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Individual ratings and range of payouts for 2012 were:</FONT></P></TD></TR>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">As discussed above, in evaluating our NEOs&#146; performance for 2012 to determine awards under the Program, the Committee used a
performance rating methodology which considered our Pre Spin-Off and our Post Spin-Off performance targets and actual results. Because the business unit rating measures performance quantitatively against three key internal measures, the Committee
retained discretionary authority to adjust the actual business rating (up or down) by as much as 25 percentage points to recognize factors which are more subjective and therefore less quantifiable&#151;such as how well we performed based on
innovation, portfolio management, talent management and the quality of our results. The Committee did not exercise its discretion to modify the business ratings in determining awards under the Program for 2012. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">While we report our financial results in accordance with U.S. GAAP, our financial targets under our incentive programs, including the Program, are based on
non-GAAP financial measures. The adjustments to the related GAAP measure and our reasons for using these measures are described in the chart below. (See Exhibit&nbsp;A on page A-1 for additional information.) </FONT></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><U>Long-Term Incentives </U></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Long-term incentive equity grants are
designed to align the interests of our executive officers with those of our shareholders. For 2012, the Committee determined that the appropriate mix of grants in our long-term incentive program for senior management, including our NEOs, was 50%
performance shares, 25% non-qualified stock options and 25% restricted stock. The same mix has been used since 2008. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g468257g69j67.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Equity Grants &#150; Non-Qualified Stock Options and Restricted Stock </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">With the objective of aligning the interests of our executives and our shareholders, historically the Committee has granted non-qualified stock options
(&#147;NQSOs&#148;) and restricted stock on an annual basis. In 2012, the Committee intended the value delivered in restricted stock be equal to the value delivered in NQSOs. To maintain this balance, based on Black-Scholes valuation, the Committee
continued to use a ratio of restricted stock to NQSOs of one to six in 2012. The Committee </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">57 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">
maintained this equity mix because it balanced the retention value of restricted stock with the performance aspect of NQSOs. To help retain valued executives, restricted stock grants do not vest
until three years after the grant date. The NQSOs vest one-third each year over three years. For non-U.S. employees, the Company grants deferred stock units instead of restricted stock, which have the same three year vesting schedule as restricted
stock. Dividends are paid on unvested restricted stock and dividend equivalents are paid on deferred stock units at the same time and rate as dividends are paid on Mondel&#275;z International common stock. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Committee bases grant ranges on an analysis of competitive market practice, with the midpoint of the equity grant ranges, inclusive of the value of the target
performance shares (see &#147;LTIP&#151;Performance Shares&#148; discussion below), approximately equal to the total long-term incentive median of the Compensation Survey Group. The Committee bases its decision to grant an equity award above or
below the midpoint on a qualitative review of the executive officer&#146;s individual performance and an evaluation of such executive officer&#146;s potential to assume roles with greater responsibility. Generally, grants are between 50% and 150% of
the midpoint. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The table below shows the ranges of grant opportunities for our NEOs on the February&nbsp;23, 2012 grant date. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

NQSOs as of the Spin-Off. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Special CEO Equity Grant </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">On December&nbsp;19, 2012, the Committee granted Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld a special equity grant valued at approximately $10,000,000. The value of the award was based on the Committee&#146;s review of other special
awards granted to other chief executive officers after major corporate transformations. Although our Company&#146;s transformation was unique to us, the special awards granted to other Chief Executive Officers were instructive in determining the
amount and design of her grant. The number of restricted shares and performance-contingent restricted stock units granted was calculated based on the intended value of the grant and the Fair Market Value (average of the high and low stock price on
the date of grant) of $25.935. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Committee intended the grant to reward Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld for: </FONT></P>

following the Spin-Off and ensure that a long-term management development and senior leadership succession plan is in place. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">To accomplish these

December&nbsp;19, 2015 (the three-year anniversary of the grant date). Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld will forfeit the applicable portion of the RSUs if the share price hurdle for the applicable tranche of
RSUs has not been satisfied prior to the earlier of: 1) December&nbsp;19, 2018 (the six-year anniversary of the grant date) or, 2) one-year following Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s retirement as CEO. She will also forfeit any unvested units as of the
date she is removed involuntarily as CEO. Further, Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld will forfeit any rights to Company stock in connection with this grant if she voluntarily leaves her position as CEO prior to December&nbsp;31, 2014, even if share price hurdles
have been satisfied for any portion of the RSUs. If the share price hurdle for the third tranche of RSUs is satisfied, Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is required to hold the net shares awarded for at least one year following her leaving the role of CEO.

the Spin-Off. Two of our NEOs received special equity grants: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Long-Term Incentive Plan &#150; Performance Shares </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The
Committee designed the LTIP to motivate executive officers to achieve long-term financial goals and top-tier shareholder returns. The Committee sets performance goals for a three year period relating to a grant. The grant made in 2012 is for the
three year period ending December&nbsp;31, 2014. At the end of the three year period, the Committee will only award Company shares if we meet or exceed performance thresholds set at the beginning of the cycle. The number of shares awarded to an
executive officer will depend on the achievement of key internal financial measures and total shareholder return results relative to our Performance Peer Group. No individual performance factor is used in the calculation, and no dividends or
dividend equivalents are paid or earned on unvested performance shares for grants made prior to 2013. For the grant made in early 2013 for the 2013-2015 performance cycle, the Committee will award dividend equivalents on shares earned for the
performance cycle. Any dividend equivalents will accrue during the performance period and be paid out in cash as of the award date for the performance cycle&#151;which generally occurs in the first quarter following the end of the performance cycle,
provided shares are awarded. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">The Committee uses the following formula to determine actual awards for participants, including our NEOs. Other than base
salary, each element of this formula is discussed below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="26%"></TD>

<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2"></TD>

Award</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="1"><B>(in&nbsp;shares)</B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>Treatment of Performance Share Units upon Spin-Off</I> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">In
order to avoid decreasing the value of participants&#146; LTIP performance share units solely as the result of the Spin-Off, the number of unvested target performance share units allocated to each LTIP participant for the 2010 &#150; 2012, 2011
&#150; 2013 and 2012 &#150; 2014 performance cycles was adjusted by a conversion ratio of 1.5266. This adjustment reflects that participants did not receive any interest in Kraft Foods Group with respect to their performance share units in the LTIP.
</FONT></P>

fluctuations (calculated based on prior year rates). Integration Program costs are defined as the costs associated with combining Mondel&#275;z International and Cadbury businesses, and are separate from those costs associated with the
acquisition.</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Reflects&nbsp;the&nbsp;growth rates for the Company&#146;s base business by eliminating the impact of certain disclosed one-time factors, facilitating comparisons to prior
year(s).</FONT></TD></TR>

acquisition-related costs, gains&nbsp;/&nbsp;losses on divestitures, pension costs related to the obligations transferred in the Spin-Off, interest expense adjustment related to the Spin-Off transaction, operating income from divested businesses and
the 2010 U.S. healthcare legislation change in prior periods.</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Reflects the growth rates for the Company&#146;s base business by eliminating the impact of certain disclosed one-time factors, facilitating comparisons to prior
year(s).</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">To address unforeseen or unintended consequences, the Committee retains discretion to adjust the final business performance rating (up or down) by as much as 25
percentage points, allowing the Committee to factor in a subjective review of quality of financial results, portfolio management, innovation and talent development. If the Committee exercises its discretion to make a limited adjustment, we will
disclose that following the conclusion of the relevant performance cycle. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">We do not publicly disclose specific long-term incentive plan targets on a prospective basis due to potential competitive harm. Revealing specific objectives
prospectively would provide competitors and other third parties with insights into our confidential planning process and strategies, thereby causing competitive harm. The performance goals are designed to be challenging, and there is a risk that
awards will not be made at all or will be made at less than 100% of the target amount. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE></div>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <div style="width:100%;margin-left:0%; margin-right:0%;background-color:#d8d8d8;padding-top:2px;padding-bottom:3px">
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="26%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Both our annual cash incentive program and our long-term incentive plan based awards are in part based on our Organic Net Revenue Growth, but the Committee uses
a somewhat different method to measure performance for these plans. The Committee measures Organic Net Revenue Growth performance under our annual cash incentive program based on our annual operating targets. In contrast, the Committee measures
Organic Net Revenue Growth under our LTIP based on our Performance Peer Group. The Committee believes that the use of these different measures focuses our executives on critical internal drivers, both in the short- and the long-term, and that the
different methods for the two incentive plans, when used together, closely correlate with shareholder value. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE></div> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Treatment of
2012-2014 Performance Cycle Upon Spin-Off: Any award made for the 2012 &#150; 2014 performance cycle will be based on a weighted average performance rating that includes the Company&#146;s performance during the Pre Spin Period (January 1, 2012
&#150; September&nbsp;30, 2012) and its performance during the Post Sppin Period (October 1, 2012 &#150; December&nbsp;31, 2014). The Committee also determined to continue using the same measures and weightings of operational goals and relative TSR
goals. However, the targets have been adjusted to reflect our Post Spin-Off attributes. With regard to determining relative TSR performance, the Pre Spin-Off Performance Peer Group was used to assess results until the Spin-Off. For the Post Spin-Off
Period, relative TSR performance will be assessed against the Post Spin-Off Performance Peer Group.</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>2011 &#150; 2013 LTIP Performance Cycle
</I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Treatment of 2011-2013 Performance Cycle Upon Spin-Off: Any award made for the 2011 &#150; 2013 performance cycle will be based on a weighted
average performance rating that includes the Company&#146;s performance during the Pre Spin Period (January 1, 2011 &#150; September&nbsp;30, 2012) and its performance during the Post Spin Period (October 1, 2012 &#150; December&nbsp;31, 2013). The
Committee also determined to continue using the same measures and weightings of operational goals and relative TSR goals. However, the targets have been adjusted to reflect our Post Spin-Off attributes. With regard to determining relative TSR
performance, the pre-Spin-Off Performance Peer Group was used to assess results until the Spin-Off. For the Post Spin-Off Period, relative TSR performance will be assessed against the Post Spin-Off Performance Peer Group.</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2"><I>2010 &#150; 2012 LTIP Performance Cycle </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:arial" SIZE="2">Each of our NEOs,
with the exception of John Cahill, participated in the 2010 &#150; 2012 LTIP. In 2010, the Committee set the performance cycle at three years; however, at the December 2011 Committee meeting, the period was shortened to 33 months (January 1, 2010
&#150; September&nbsp;30, 2012) due to the Spin-Off. Following the Spin-Off, the Committee determined that the LTIP rating for the Pre Spin-Off Period was 160%, and awarded shares based on this rating. Because the performance period was set to end
within three months of the Spin-Off, the Committee truncated the performance cycle so that the award would be based solely on the Company&#146;s performance during the 33-month Pre Spin-Off Period. The Committee applied time-based vesting for the
remaining period. </FONT></P>
